Water infrastructure

Fred Ramos

Sample of Cities

The sample includes 56 cities distributed around all the continents, with few cities in Europe and North America. The interactive map bellow shows the spatial distribution of the cities with simbols proportional to the city size.

The data set includes the measurement of urban extent depicted by satellite imagery in different periods around the years 1990, 2000 and 2015. The availability of census data in different periods varies across the sample and was organized in ways that is most close the period when the images are available. The observations were then aggregated in 3 time period: T1, T2 and T3. The scatter plot bellow shows the distribution of the year when the census data was collected and the year of the satellite imagery.

Access to water

Analyzing the evolution of the access to piped water is possible to observe a diversity of situations across the cities. Cities in Latin America managed to consistently increase the provision of piped water over the period. In the same period, some cities couldn`t manage to guarantee the access.

The general evolution by continent shows that some cities in Asia and Africa had worsened the access over the three periods.

The evolution of the population of the city and the access to piped water follows specific patterns by city. In general, the most populous cities managed to increase the access for piped water being Manila the remarkable exception of this group.

For some cities, the census data provides more detailed information about the type of water provision differentiating those that have access to piped water inside of the household form those that have access only outside as a collective infrastructure.
